### Absorption, Distribution and Excretion

Metformin is slowly and incompletely absorbed from the GI tract, mainly from the small intestine; absorption is complete within 6 hours. The absolute {{ drug.route_of_administration }} bioavailability of the drug under fasting conditions is reported to be approximately 50-60% with {{ drug.name }} doses of 0.5-1.{{ drug.strength }}; binding of the drug to the intestinal wall may explain the difference between the amount of drug absorbed (as determined by the urinary and fecal excretion of unchanged drug) and the amount bioavailable in some studies. In single-dose studies with {{ drug.name }} conventional {{ drug.dosage_form }} doses of 0.5-1.{{ drug.strength }} or 0.85-2.{{ drug.strength }}, plasma metformin concentrations did not increase in proportion to increasing doses, suggesting an active saturable absorption process. Similarly, in single-dose studies with an extended-release {{ drug.dosage_form }} preparation (Glumetza) at doses of 0.5-2.{{ drug.strength }}, plasma metforminconcentrations did not increase in proportion to increasing doses. At steady state after administration of a {{ drug.name }} extended-release {{ drug.dosage_form }} preparation (Glucophage XR), the {{ drug.molecular_formula }} and peak plasma concentrations were not dose proportional within the range of 0.5-{{ drug.strength }}. However, limited data from studies in animals and in human intestinal cell cultures suggest that transepithelial transfer of metformin in the intestine may occur through a passive, nonsaturable mechanism, possibly involving a paracellular route. In several studies with another {{ drug.name }} extended-release {{ drug.dosage_form }} preparation (Fortamet) using doses of 1-2.{{ drug.strength }}, metforminexposure was dose-related.

American Society of Health-System Pharmacists 2016; Drug Information 2016. Bethesda, MD. 2016, p. 3202-3

