Metformin is the most commonly prescribed {{ drug.route_of_administration }} antidiabetic drug, with well-documented beneficial preventive effects on diabetic complications. Despite being in clinical use for almost 60 years, the underlying mechanisms for metformin action remain elusive. Organic cation transporters ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}), including multidrug and toxin extrusion proteins ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}), are essential for transport of metformin across membranes, but tissue-specific activity of these transporters in vivo is incompletely understood. Here, we use dynamic positron emission tomography with [(11)C]-labeled metformin ([(11)C]-metformin) in mice to investigate the role of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} and {{ drug.molecular_formula }} in a well-established target tissue, the liver, and a putative target of metformin, the small intestine. Ablation of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} and {{ drug.molecular_formula }} significantly reduced the distribution of metformin in the liver and small intestine. In contrast, inhibition of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} with pyrimethaminecaused accumulation of metformin in the liver but did not affect distribution in the small intestine. The demonstration of {{ drug.molecular_formula }}-mediated transport into the small intestine provides evidence of direct effects of metforminin this tissue. {{ drug.molecular_formula }} and {{ drug.molecular_formula }} have important but separate roles in uptake and elimination of metformin in the liver, but this is not due to changes in biliary secretion. [(11)C]-Metformin holds great potential as a tool to determine the pharmacokinetic properties of metformin in clinical studies.
